## Delegating Constructors

When a class has multiple constructors, they often share initialization logic. Without delegating constructors, you'd either duplicate that logic or extract it into a private helper function. Delegating constructors let one constructor call another constructor in the same class directly in the member initializer list, eliminating that duplication cleanly.

The syntax looks like a member initializer list entry, but the target is the class name itself:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

struct Player {
    std::string name;
    int health;
    int level;

    Player(std::string name, int health, int level)
        : name{std::move(name)}, health{health}, level{level} {}

    // Delegates to the three-parameter constructor
    Player(std::string name, int health)
        : Player{std::move(name), health, 1} {}

    // Delegates further
    explicit Player(std::string name)
        : Player{std::move(name), 100} {}
};
```

Here the two-parameter constructor delegates to the three-parameter one, and the one-parameter constructor delegates to the two-parameter one, forming a chain. Only the final target constructor actually initializes the members.

**Key rules to keep in mind:**

- A delegating constructor cannot also initialize members directly in its own initializer list — the entire initializer list is consumed by the delegation call. If you need member-specific initialization on top of delegation, do it in the constructor body instead.
- Delegation chains must not be circular. `A` calling `B` calling `A` is undefined behavior and most compilers will warn or error.
- The delegated-to constructor runs first, completely, before the body of the delegating constructor executes. This is useful when you need post-construction adjustments in the delegating constructor's body.

**Why prefer this over a private `init()` helper?**

A private helper function runs after all members are constructed (since member initialization happens before any function body). With complex types, that means members are default-constructed first and then overwritten. Delegation avoids that extra construction step by wiring directly into the member initializer list phase, as covered in *Constructor member initializer lists*.

Delegating constructors pair naturally with default arguments (see *Default constructors and default arguments*). Sometimes a single constructor with default arguments is simpler, but delegation is preferable when the logic between overloads genuinely differs beyond just supplying missing values.

